<font color="#FF0000">REPLY TO TANYA</font><br>
<tt>Tue Dec 17 14:48:57 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
Dear Tanya,<br><br>
Thank you for your reply. I first spoke to Viet Nam veteran in 1966 when I was working at the U.S. Naval Medical Research Unit, #3 (NAMRU-3) in Cairo, Egypt. These vets were corpsmen who had rotated out from Viet Nam and were subsequently stationed in the NAMRU-3 hospital. Medical corpsmen and nurses have a distinctly different view of war than most..... they were the ones who administered to the wounded and dying, who listened for heart sounds and pulses, who heard too many last words. Corpsmen and nurses: we should all offer thanks that we did not have to see what they saw, or hear what they heard.<br><br>
I have been speaking to vets ever since.<br><br>
I also have had much to learn, through the years, after speaking with Quakers, especially Friends who worked in Viet Nam after 1975. <br><br>
Tanya, as you realize, most Americans who lived through the Vietnam era will have strong views, whether in support of or against the war. At one time in my life I also believed strongly in the lessons of Munich, in the Domino Theory. When I visit the Wall in Washington, D.C. I reach out and touch a name at random, I rub my fingers over the polished letters, and I whisper thank you; and I continue to thank each veteran who gave his or her life... and I whisper to each my belief that their sacrifice was not in vain. And the living vets... I thank them as well.<br><br>
Scroll the web sites related to the wall.... pull up the files of the directory of names; they range alphabetically from Gerald L. Aadland to David Lee Zywicke; scroll then across your computer screen; the names seem endless but they tally approximately 58,000.<br><br>
For the past four years I have been working on nutrition-related problems in Viet Nam. There, the cemeteries seem endless. No one has tallied all the Vietnamese dead (both North and South); some estimates range as high as 2,000,000.<br><br>
I have a dear friend, a Vietnamese. In 1993 he invited me to go to the cemetery northwest of Sai Gon where his father, a North Vietnamese Regular, lies buried. We placed offerings of fruit, flowers, paper money, upon the grave and lit sticks of jos. As the smoke spiraled... my Vietnamese friend took my hand and said:<br><br>
&quot;Louis, my father would have liked you.&quot; <br><br>
This is why I remain haunted..... as someone once said: we get smart too late in life!<br><br>
Thank you for responding to this &quot;dialog string.&quot;<br><br>
Regards and best wishes,<br><br>

<p><code>-- legrivetti@ucdavis.edu  (Louis E. Grivetti) </code><p>


